From: NextOS Elite Edition
Subject: [PATCH] Drop GLES1OnGL2 fallback on Linux

NextOS targets Mali-450 (Amlogic-old) which exposes OpenGL ES 1.1 / 2.0
but has no desktop OpenGL 2.1 compatibility profile. The GLES1OnGL2
backend tries to create a desktop GL 2.1 context, fails, and ends up
masking the real error from GLES1Native with a misleading "GL 2.1
unavailable" message.

On Linux, restrict the implementation list to GLES1Native so that
either it works, or we fail fast with the actual GLES1.1 error.

Other platforms (Windows, macOS) keep the upstream fallback chain.

diff --git a/src/gles.rs b/src/gles.rs
--- a/src/gles.rs
+++ b/src/gles.rs
@@ -84,7 +84,15 @@ pub enum GLESImplementation {
 }
 impl GLESImplementation {
     /// List of OpenGL ES 1.1 implementations in order of preference.
+    ///
+    /// On Linux (NextOS targets Mali-450 with GLES 1.1 / 2.0 only — no
+    /// desktop GL 2.1 compat profile), drop GLES1OnGL2 so a missing
+    /// libGLESv1_CM doesn't get silently masked by a confusing "GL 2.1
+    /// not available" error from the fallback path.
+    #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
+    pub const GLES1_IMPLEMENTATIONS: &'static [Self] = &[Self::GLES1Native];
+    #[cfg(not(target_os = "linux"))]
     pub const GLES1_IMPLEMENTATIONS: &'static [Self] = &[Self::GLES1Native, Self::GLES1OnGL2];
     /// Convert from short name used for command-line arguments. Returns [Err]
     /// if name is not recognized..
     pub fn from_short_name(name: &str) -> Result<Self, ()> {
